    },
    {
      "id": "06055e286ce61f9dc0841c9b30f2c9028af8e970",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 131,
        "name": "Jian Yu",
        "email": "yujian@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "yujian"
      },
      "date": "2012-08-15 13:48:12.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\n> Tests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.3/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/2efb4d78-e6d7-11e1-80c3-52540035b04c). Ran 1 tests. 1 tests failed: mmp.\n\n 05:37:44:CMD: fat-intel-3vm3 /usr/lib64/lustre/tests/e2fsck.exp /dev/lvm-MDS/P1\n 05:37:49:CMD: fat-intel-3vm3 mkdir -p /mnt/mds1\n 05:37:50:CMD: fat-intel-3vm3 test -b /dev/lvm-MDS/P1\n 05:37:54:spawn e2fsck -f /dev/lvm-MDS/P1\n\n 05:37:54:e2fsck 1.42.3.wc3 (15-Aug-2012)\n 05:37:55:Starting mds1: -o user_xattr,acl  /dev/lvm-MDS/P1 /mnt/mds1\n 05:37:55:CMD: fat-intel-3vm3 mkdir -p /mnt/mds1; mount -t lustre -o user_xattr,acl /dev/lvm-MDS/P1 /mnt/mds1\n\nIt's strange that e2fsck.exp was performed on 05:37:44, but \"spawn e2fsck -f /dev/lvm-MDS/P1\" was called 10 seconds later.\n\nIt's also weird that the real mount operation was started right after e2fsck was started, the mount operation should fail but not.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "8824dc5699477d4f0b6ae72a9f374f6af9e11f69",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2012-08-15 14:09:40.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\nTests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.3/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/3c5574d2-e6df-11e1-80c3-52540035b04c).  Ran 12 tests.  1 tests failed: sanity.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "e9c883c6607df552271f2a4720869b2239634503",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 131,
        "name": "Jian Yu",
        "email": "yujian@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "yujian"
      },
      "date": "2012-08-15 14:53:02.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\n> Tests received by maloo, run on CentOS release 6.3/x86_64: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/3c5574d2-e6df-11e1-80c3-52540035b04c). Ran 12 tests. 1 tests failed: sanity.\n\nIn the above test session, the mmp test 8 passed:\n\n 06:37:43:CMD: client-25vm7 /usr/lib64/lustre/tests/e2fsck.exp /dev/lvm-MDS/P1\n 06:37:48:CMD: client-25vm7 mkdir -p /mnt/mds1\n 06:37:49:CMD: client-25vm7 test -b /dev/lvm-MDS/P1\n 06:37:49:Starting mds1: -o user_xattr,acl  /dev/lvm-MDS/P1 /mnt/mds1\n 06:37:49:CMD: client-25vm7 mkdir -p /mnt/mds1; mount -t lustre -o user_xattr,acl /dev/lvm-MDS/P1 /mnt/mds1\n 06:37:49:client-25vm7: mount.lustre: mount /dev/dm-0 at /mnt/mds1 failed: Device or resource busy\n 06:37:49:Start of /dev/lvm-MDS/P1 on mds1 failed 16\n 06:37:53:spawn e2fsck -f /dev/lvm-MDS/P1\n 06:37:53:e2fsck 1.42.3.wc3 (15-Aug-2012)\n\nSo, as we can see, it seemed \"spawn e2fsck -f /dev/lvm-MDS/P1\" was called 10 seconds later after e2fsck.exp was performed, but in fact not, it was only a delayed message outputted while performing \"wait $e2fsck_pid\". The \"e2fsck 1.42.3.wc3 (15-Aug-2012)\" was also a delayed output message. The real e2fsck operation has been started before the real mount operation.\n\nFor the previously failed case:\n\n 05:37:44:CMD: fat-intel-3vm3 /usr/lib64/lustre/tests/e2fsck.exp /dev/lvm-MDS/P1\n 05:37:49:CMD: fat-intel-3vm3 mkdir -p /mnt/mds1\n 05:37:50:CMD: fat-intel-3vm3 test -b /dev/lvm-MDS/P1\n 05:37:54:spawn e2fsck -f /dev/lvm-MDS/P1\n 05:37:54:e2fsck 1.42.3.wc3 (15-Aug-2012)\n 05:37:55:Starting mds1: -o user_xattr,acl  /dev/lvm-MDS/P1 /mnt/mds1\n 05:37:55:CMD: fat-intel-3vm3 mkdir -p /mnt/mds1; mount -t lustre -o user_xattr,acl /dev/lvm-MDS/P1 /mnt/mds1\n 05:38:18:CMD: fat-intel-3vm3 e2label /dev/lvm-MDS/P1 2>/dev/null\n 05:38:18:Started lustre-MDT0000\n\nThe real mount operation was started after e2fsck operation was finished. So, we need increase the sleep time in e2fsck.exp.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
